{{Infobox person | name = Frank Sargent Hoffman | image = Frank Sargent Hoffman.png |birth_date = February 9, 1852 |death_date = 1928 | occupation = [[Philosopher]]}}
'''Frank Sargent Hoffman''' (February 9, 1852 - 1928) was an American [[philosopher]] who wrote on [[psychology]] and [[religion]].
Hoffman was born in [[Sheboygan Falls, Wisconsin]]. In 1876 he graduated from [[Amherst College]] and obtained his PhD in 1896. He received a [[Bachelor of Divinity]] degree from [[Yale University]].<ref name="Vranken">[[Andrew Van Vranken Raymond|Raymond, Andrew Van Vranken]]. (1907). [https://archive.org/stream/unionuniversity02raymgoog#page/n12/mode/2up ''Union University, Its History, Influence, Characteristics and Equipment'']. Volume 2. pp. 5-7</ref> He was Professor of Philosophy at [[Union College]]. He contributed to ''[[The North American Review]]'' and was a member of the [[American Philosophical Association]], [[American Psychology Society]] and the [[Phi Beta Kappa Society]].<ref name="Vranken"/>
Hoffman's ''Psychology and Common Life'' (1903) received mixed reviews, a criticism was its overemphasise on [[psychical research]].<ref>Pillsbury, W. B. (1904). [https://www.jstor.org/stable/2176463 ''Reviewed Work: Psychology and Common Life by Frank Sargent Hoffman'']. ''[[The Philosophical Review]]'' 13 (2): 254-255.</ref><ref>Urban, Wilbur M. (1904). ''Reviewed Work: Psychology and Common Life by Frank Sargent Hoffman''. ''[[The Journal of Philosophy|The Journal of Philosophy, Psychology and Scientific Methods]]'' 1 (7): 183-184.</ref>
