'''{{Lang|la|Mater semper certa est}}''' ("The mother is always certain") is a [[Roman law|Roman-law]]  principle which has the power of {{Lang|la|[[conclusive presumption|praesumptio iuris et de iure]]}}, meaning that no counter-evidence can be made against this principle (literally: Presumed there is no counter evidence and by the law). Its meaning is that the mother of the child is always known.<ref name="ZweigertDrobnig1991">{{cite book|author1=K. Zweigert|author2=K. Drobnig|title=International Encyclopedia of Comparative Law|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=wKPET7pA_4MC&pg=PA28|date=1 January 1991|publisher=BRILL|pages=28–|id=GGKEY:1LUWFFPE9KR}}</ref> 

Since 1978, when the first child was conceived by the technique of [[In vitro fertilisation|''in-vitro'' fertilization]], the principle of {{Lang|la|Mater semper certa est}} no longer applies, since a child may have a ''genetic'' and a ''natural'' ("[[birth]]") mother who are different individuals. Since then some countries have converted the old natural law to an equivalent [[Codification (law)|codified law]] - in 1997 Germany introduced paragraph 1571 {{Lang|de|Mutterschaft}} ("motherhood") of the [[Bürgerliches Gesetzbuch|BGB]] ([[civil code]]) reading {{Lang|de|Mutter eines Kindes ist die Frau, die es geboren hat}} ("the mother of a child is the woman who gave birth to it"). 

The Roman law principle however does not stop at the mother, in fact it continues with {{Lang|la|pater semper incertus est}} ("The father is always uncertain"). This was regulated by the law of {{Lang|la|pater est, quem nuptiae demonstrant}} ("the father is he to whom marriage points"). Essentially [[paternity fraud]] had originally been a marriage fraud in the civil code<ref group="note">In Germany, the historic {{Lang|de|Ehelichkeitsanfechtungsklage}} ("action in dispute of legitimacy") was simply renamed as {{Lang|de|Vaterschaftsanfechtungsklage}} ("action in dispute of fatherhood") when [[paternity (law)|legal paternity]] was redefined.{{CN|date=March 2017}}</ref> due to this principle. Today some married fathers use the modern tools of [[DNA testing]] to ensure a certainty on their fatherhood.<ref>{{ cite news | url=http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,1580398-1,00.html | work=Time Magazine U.S. | location= | title=Duped Dads Fight Back | date=19 January 2007 | first=Julie | last=Rawe }}</ref>

